    slug: "sharah-umdat-ul-ehkaam-pashto",
    description: `Sharah Umdat ul Ehkaam (Pashto) is a Pashto-language commentary on the renowned Islamic jurisprudence text Umdat al-Ahkam, one of the most widely studied hadith-based books in the field of fiqh (Islamic jurisprudence). Umdat al-Ahkam is a carefully curated collection of hadith narrations from Sahih al-Bukhari and Sahih Muslim that cover the major rulings of Islamic law, including purification, prayer, fasting, zakat, hajj, trade, marriage, divorce, and criminal law. This Pashto-language sharah makes this essential fiqh text accessible to the Pashto-speaking population, particularly in Afghanistan and the Pashtun regions of Pakistan, who may not be able to study the text in its original Arabic or in Urdu translations.

The book follows the structure of Umdat al-Ahkam, organizing the hadith narrations by topic and providing a detailed explanation of each narration. For each hadith, the commentary includes the full Arabic text with diacritical marks, a Pashto translation of the text, an explanation of the key vocabulary and legal terminology, and a discussion of the fiqh ruling that is derived from the narration. The author presents the positions of the four major schools of Islamic jurisprudence (Hanafi, Maliki, Shafi'i, and Hanbali) on each issue, enabling readers to understand the range of scholarly opinion within the broader framework of Islamic law. Where the schools differ, the commentary explains the evidence and reasoning behind each position, allowing readers to appreciate the richness of Islamic legal scholarship.

The commentary also addresses the chain of narrators (isnad) of each hadith, providing brief biographical notes on the key narrators and discussing the grading of each narration in terms of its authenticity. This feature makes the book valuable not only for fiqh but also as an introduction to the science of hadith for Pashto-speaking students. The book covers all the essential topics of daily Islamic practice, including the conditions and pillars of wudu (ablution) and ghusl (ritual bathing), the requirements and recommended acts of the five daily prayers, the rules for congregational and Friday prayers, the fiqh of fasting during Ramadan, the calculation and distribution of zakat, the rituals of hajj and umrah, the Islamic ethics of business transactions, the rules governing marriage and family life, and the principles of Islamic criminal justice. Sharah Umdat ul Ehkaam (Pashto) is an indispensable resource for Pashto-speaking Muslims who wish to understand their religion through its primary sources and the established scholarly tradition.`,
