    slug: "shifaat-ka-bayan",
    description: `Shifa'at Ka Bayan is an Urdu-language Islamic book that provides a detailed and scholarly exposition of the concept of shifa'ah (intercession) in Islam — the belief that Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) and other righteous servants of Allah will be granted the privilege of interceding on behalf of others on the Day of Judgment. The book addresses this important theological topic with comprehensive coverage of the Quranic verses, hadith narrations, and scholarly opinions that define the Islamic understanding of intercession, clearing up common misconceptions and presenting the orthodox position with clarity and depth.

The book establishes the fundamental principle that all intercession belongs exclusively to Allah, as stated in the Quran, and that no one can intercede except by His permission and for those whom He approves. This foundational principle distinguishes the Islamic concept of intercession from the beliefs of other religions where intercession is seen as an inherent right of certain individuals. The author then discusses the various types of intercession that are established in the authentic sources, beginning with the Greatest Intercession (al-shafa'ah al-kubra) — the unique privilege of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) to begin the reckoning on the Day of Judgment and to intercede for the entire creation. This event is described in detail using the hadith narrations that depict the scene on the Day of Judgment, the people's desperation as they approach the prophets seeking someone to intercede for them, and the ultimate granting of this honor to Prophet Muhammad.

The book covers additional types of intercession, including intercession for the people of major sins among the Muslim community, intercession for believers to enter Paradise without reckoning, intercession to elevate the ranks of believers in Paradise, and intercession for some members of the Muslim community who deserve punishment to have their punishment reduced. The author also discusses the intercession of other prophets, the angels, the righteous believers, and the martyrs, each within the boundaries established by the Quran and Sunnah. The book carefully distinguishes between intercession that is supported by authentic evidence and intercession that is claimed without basis, addressing the erroneous beliefs that have crept into some Muslim communities regarding intercession through saints, shrines, and the deceased. Throughout the work, the author maintains a balanced approach, affirming the established reality of intercession while warning against the excesses that can lead to shirk (associating partners with Allah). Shifa'at Ka Bayan is an essential reference for anyone seeking a correct and thorough understanding of this important article of Islamic faith.`,
